Stephen Rees-Cartersays:
December 9, 2020 at 11:21 am
I‚Äôve seen that happen a couple of times. I‚Äôve always assumed it‚Äôs just differences between the filesystems (win vs linux) that can cause rsync to think the file is changed. In some cases it has resolved itself, but others it seems to always copy each time.
There are some rsync options you could play around with like --checksum, which use different comparison methods. They could result in a faster sync (with less files), although checksum may be slow if you‚Äôve a lot of large files. So it‚Äôs a bit of a tradeoff to find the right option that works for you‚Ä¶
You can find the options on the rsync manpage: https://linux.die.net/man/1/rsync

